<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="261" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,570,1475]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,570,595]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">Description.</emphasis>
Abdomen: Syntergite 
<number box="[550,560,571,595]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="1.0">1</number>
+ 
<number box="[578,594,571,595]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="2.0">2</number>
very large, 
<date box="[727,761,571,595]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
<number box="[727,741,571,595]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="4.0">4</number>
X
</date>
length of T 
<number box="[895,908,571,595]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="3.0">3</number>
, with a large pale anteromedial area and a dark posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,570,1475]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
Male abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[381,491,641,666]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 8" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1912,1935]" captionTargetBox="[172,1433,409,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,409,1891]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 8. Albistyla occulta male abdomen. 6, ventral; 7, sternite 5; 8, phallus and associated structures left lateral, with hypandrium. Figs. 9 – 10: Albistyla females, spermathecae. 9, A. occulta; 10, A. spatulisterna. Abbreviations: S 3 – 5, sternites 3 – 5." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/224476/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
Figs. 
<number box="[445,491,641,666]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="7.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="6.0">6–8</number>
</figureCitation>
): Posterior margin of S 
<number box="[751,765,641,666]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="5.0">5</number>
complex, each side with a single large bristle and a trilobed spatulate process, outer lobes dark, cup-shaped and widely separated; middle lobes elongate, tuberculate, setose and projecting ventrally; inner lobes shallowly fimbriate. Epandrium and surstylus as described for 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Albistyla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spatulisterna">A. spatulisterna</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Basiphallus with a prominent and apically rounded posterior process (epiphallus); distiphallus very short, tubular; lightly sclerotized but setulose along broadly expanded flanged distal margin. Postgonite with a large anterobasal tubercle articulating with a bisetose pregonite, distal part of postgonite strongly tapered and curved anteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[358,426,852,877]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 8" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1912,1935]" captionTargetBox="[172,1433,409,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,409,1891]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 8. Albistyla occulta male abdomen. 6, ventral; 7, sternite 5; 8, phallus and associated structures left lateral, with hypandrium. Figs. 9 – 10: Albistyla females, spermathecae. 9, A. occulta; 10, A. spatulisterna. Abbreviations: S 3 – 5, sternites 3 – 5." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/224476/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
Fig. 
<number box="[411,426,853,877]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,570,1475]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261">
Female abdomen: T 
<number box="[427,440,888,911]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="7.0">7</number>
and T 
<number box="[516,529,888,912]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="8.0">8</number>
complete, only slightly shortened dorsomedially, with only a few small bristles on posterior margin. T 
<number box="[411,438,923,947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="10.0">10</number>
greatly reduced, bare. Posterior margin of S 
<number box="[951,965,923,947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="7.0">7</number>
convex and weakly bilobed; S 
<number box="[1323,1337,923,947]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="8.0">8</number>
hyaline, transverse and with a transverse row of 
<number box="[604,618,958,982]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="4.0">4</number>
small equal bristles. S 
<number box="[875,904,958,982]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="10.0">10</number>
densely setulose, without bristles. Cercus very short and rounded, no longer than broad, with 
<number box="[701,715,993,1017]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="4.0">4</number>
short bristles. Spermathecae with a funnel-shaped base and a ridged, tire-shaped distal part; ducts with a U-shaped bend just beyond base, sclerotized part as long as spermathecal body (Fig. 
<number box="[429,446,1064,1088]" pageId="4" pageNumber="261" value="9.0">9</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
